R-CDs was prepared by hydrothermal treatment of PPD as described in the Experimental section (Scheme 1
                     ) [39]. As shown in Fig. 1
                     , the photoluminescence (PL) properties including UV–vis absorption and FL spectra of R-CDs have been investigated. The absorption peaks at 242 and 285 nm in the UV–vis absorption spectrum of R-CDs can be attributed to the n-σ* (C-NH/C-OH) and π-π* (C = C/C = N) transitions, respectively. The absorption peak at 501 nm can be assigned as n-π* transition containing C-O and C = O structures (Fig. 1a) [40]. The FL emission peak of R-CDs is located at 610 nm (Fig. 1b). Notably, although the excitation-wavelength increased from 340 to 530 nm, the emission of R-CDs is fixed at 610 nm, showing that R-CDs have excitation-wavelength independent FL properties [21], and the obtained R-CDs ethanol solutions exhibit an absolute QY (quantum yield) of 11.39% (Ex: 468 nm) under ambient conditions.

Interestingly, as shown in Scheme 2
                     , after adding SA into R-CDs solution, the FL changes significantly from the red color of R-CDs solutions to the bright yellow color of Y-CDs powders (Fig. 3
                     ). The aldehyde groups are well recognized for quickly reacting with amino groups via the C = N binding Schiff base reaction [45–47]. During this process, the aldehyde group of SA could accept the attack of amino groups of R-CDs, resulting in imine production reactions. The as-prepared Y-CDs have been characterized with the zeta potential and FT-IR spectrum to confirm the nature of the CDs-based luminescent materials. The zeta potential of Y-CDs is + 5.5 mV (Fig. S1), indicating that low positive charge functional groups present over the Y-CDs’ surface, giving the system lower stability and higher aggregability [48–49]. The FT-IR spectrum of Y-CDs is shown in Fig. S2, after functionalization with the SA-based ligands, the C = N stretching bands increases the intensity, whilst new peaks appeared 738 cm−1 associated with Ar-H vibrations, confirming that the ligands were successfully attached to the R-CDs [50]. The AIE property of Y-CDs are investigated in powders, DMSO solutions and H2O/DMSO mixtures. As presented in Fig. 3b (right), Y-CDs are non-emissive when dissolved in a good solvent DMSO, while their emission are turned on when the Y-CDs in solid-state with a high quantum yield up to 19.96% (Fig. 3b, left). In addition, we have also studied the AIE performance of Y-CDs in H2O/DMSO mixtures, as shown in Fig. S3, with the increasing fraction of H2O volume from 50% to 90%, the FL intensity of Y-CDs was significantly enhanced, showing obvious characteristics of AIE [46]. The possible mechanism for AIE property of Y-CDs is when Y-CDs are in the aggregated state, surface ligands formed by SA acted to block aggregation of the graphitized cores. Thus, ACQ phenomena caused by direct π-π interactions caused by the carbon cores stacking was avoided. On the other hand, hydrogen bonds formed by the hydroxyl groups from SA and carbon cores, enhancing aggregation-induced emission effect [50].
